SIMPLE: tomb
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tomb
<hw>Tomb</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tombe</ets>,
<ets>toumbe</ets>, F. <ets>tombe</ets>, LL. <ets>tumba</ets>, fr. Gr.
<?/ a tomb, grave; perhaps akin to L. <ets>tumulus</ets> a mound. Cf.
<er>Tumulus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pit in which the dead body
of a human being is deposited; a grave; a sepulcher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As one dead in the bottom of a <qex>tomb</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A house or vault, formed wholly or partly in the
earth, with walls and a roof, for the reception of the dead.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>tomb</xex> of marble stones.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A monument erected to inclose the body and preserve
the name and memory of the dead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hang her an epitaph upon her <qex>tomb</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tomb bat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of
species of Old World bats of the genus <gen>Taphozous</gen> which
inhabit tombs, especially the Egyptian species (<spn>Taphozous
perforatus</spn>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tomb</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tomb
<hw>Tomb</hw>,, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tombed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tombing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To place in a tomb; to bury; to
inter; to entomb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>tombed</qex> my brother that I might be blessed.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tombac</ent>⟦br⟧
